ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.3bcb087c-cf9f-4e00-9cf5-b9dbc8daf9ea.prompt=UsernamePrompt\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.3f9a9959-aa21-47da-9dbf-af6918007739.prompt=PrivateKeyFile\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.55f32c4b-234a-4295-978e-18f05d4e6b63.prompt=PasswordPrompt\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.5a47f1ba-b5cd-4b54-a7d8-97ef583bfd71.prompt=Timeout\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.5f39085d-3534-47fb-ac96-7ebbe3368243.prompt=Pty\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.83eaa8b8-b5b9-4ffa-a14a-6cfcdbf6ddc6.prompt=OutputPath\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.89ade38f-fc71-4b7c-82f7-a3003bde4ee4.prompt=Device\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.8a419103-43f6-4b48-adc3-c6ae3565d8e8.prompt=SasHostUsername\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.98b6db90-3711-49c4-bff4-e0a3b6f34c62.prompt=Protocol\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.98e5b323-bbe2-4eca-ab29-5c918f898098.prompt=SasHost\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.9fff0432-5e8d-4eca-85b1-3b11807e33ff.prompt=Password\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.ba3e607d-007a-49d1-943c-fae6e6510cbf.prompt=Username\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.c0a03af6-383e-4cda-a16f-8370a51ce891.prompt=Enter host\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.d727a108-f493-4b2c-96e8-45474dc922c1.prompt=Host\: ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.description=
This retrieves disk metrics using iostat
The result values are taken after two calls of iostat command.
The current extra parameters represents the values after the second call.

Inputs\:

host\:  the system to check
username\: the user to log into this system as
password\: the password to log in with
device\: disk name (Device) to check
port - port number for connecting to the host
protocol - the protocol used to run the command (can be one of ssh, ROSH, GlobalShell, Telnet, RSH, local)
timeout - (optional, default 90 seconds) time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete
pty - (true, false) whether to use pty
privateKeyFile - The absolute path to the private key file for remote host.
sasHost - the host we want to run the ROSH command on
sasHostUsername - the username used to run the ROSH command on sasHost
usernamePrompt - the prompt that when seen should send the username
passwordPrompt - the prompt that when given should send the password
outputPath - network accessible path used by the operation to store temporary files. If not specified it points to \\host\admin$\temp\'. If this path is not accessible you should change it to use another share that the host local system account has write access to. By default, the path will have to be  changed on Windows 2000 systems

Responses\:

success\: the data was obtained
failure\: the data could not be obtained

Result\:

Code - the return code of the iostat command

Extra Results\:

averageBusyPercent - The average percent of time when the device was active
averageKBReadPerSecond - The average amount of data read from the drive
averageKBWritePerSecond - The average amount of data written to the drive
averageReadsPerSecond - The average number of reading operation
averageServiceTime - The average service time per operation (milliseconds)
averageServiceTimeInWaitQueue - The average service time in the waiting queue
averageTransactionsServiced - The average number of transactions  actively being serviced (removed  from  the queue but not yet completed)
averageTransactionsWaiting - The average number of transactions waiting
averageWaitPercent - The average percent of time there are transactions  waiting for service (queue non-empty)
averageWritesPerSecond - The average number of write operations
currentBusyPercent - The last percent of time when the device was active
currentKBReadPerSecond - The last amount of data read from the drive
currentKBWritePerSecond - The last amount of data written to the drive
currentReadsPerSecond - The last number of reading operations
currentServiceTime - The last service time per operation (milliseconds)
currentServiceTimeInWaitQueue - The last service time in the waiting queue
currentTransactionsServiced - The last number of transactions  actively being serviced (removed  from  the queue but not yet completed)
currentTransactionsWaiting - The last number of transactions waiting
currentWaitPercent - The last value of percent of time there are transactions  waiting for service (queue non-empty)
currentWritesPerSecond - The last number of write operation
totalErrors - The total number of errors during the operations
Error String - STDERR of the command
Output String - STDOUT of the command
ee03cbdd-ebe1-4962-9eff-259d27b5272c.f3ca0b1f-fe27-4530-953a-bdee6a172a24.description=
Runs a command and allows user to specify that it runs locally (in this case no port should be specified), via ssh, Global Shell, ROSH, Telnet, or RSH.

Inputs\:
host - hostname or ip address
port - port number for connecting to the host
username - username to connect as
password - password
protocol - the protocol used to run the command (can be one of ssh, ROSH, GlobalShell, Telnet, RSH, local, or NASConnectTelnet)
timeout - (optional, default 90 seconds) time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete
command - the command to execute
arguments - the arguments to pass to the command
environment - specifies environment variables/values that need to be defined when running command
startDir - the path to the starting directory
pty - (true, false) whether to use pty
privateKeyFile - The absolute path to the private key file for remote host.
sasHost - the host we want to run the ROSH command on
sasHostUsername - the username used to run the ROSH command on sasHost
usernamePrompt - the prompt that when seen should send the username; used by the Telnet protocol; when used by the NASConnectTelnet protocol, the default value is 'NAS Login\:'
passwordPrompt - the prompt that when given should send the password; used by the Telnet protocol; when used by the NASConnectTelnet protocol, the default value is 'Password\:'
outputPath - network accessible path used by the operation to store temporary files. If not specified it points to \\host\admin$\temp\'. If this     path is not accessible you should change it to use another share that the host local system account has write access to. By default, the path will have to be  changed on Windows 2000 systems
nasDevice - The NAS device to run the command on when using the NAS connect API protocol.

Responses\:
success - the command was executed successfully
failure - the command could not be executed

Extra Results\:
stdErr - the STDERR of the command
stdOut - the STDOUT of the command
